ory of corruption by examining the English East India Company and its transformation from a largely commercial enterprise to a militarized offshoot of British empire in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. He argues that the modern idea of corruption arose as an unintended consequence of conflicts among company officials and the changing audiences to which they justified themselves in Britain. This new understanding unified an imperial elite at risk of fragmenting into irreconcilable moral worlds and, in the process, helped redefine the boundaries of state, society, and economy. Modernity’s Corruption is at once a novel historical sociology of imperial administration and its contradictions, a fresh argument about the nature of corruption and its political and organizational effects, and a reinvigoration of classic arguments about the nature and consequences of global modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCorruptionxHistoryy18th century. 0aCorruptionxHistoryy19th century. 0aGreat BritainxMoral conditionszCase studies. 0aPublic administrationxCorrupt practiceszIndia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Corruption & Misconduct .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/wils1921840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231549707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231549707/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles